******
[2] Greece
Date: Thu 19 Jul 2018
Source: Ekathimerini [edited]
http://www.ekathimerini.com/230870/article/ekathimerini/news/number-of-people-infected-with-west-nile-virus-rises-to-12


The number of people in Greece believed to have contracted West Nile virus, which is carried by infected mosquitoes, has risen to 12, the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (KEELPNO) said on [Wed 18 Jul 2018] in its weekly epidemiological data posted on its website.

The cases have been reported in the Attica municipalities of Ilioupoli, Megara and Tanagra, and in Halkidona, Thessaloniki, KEELPNO said.

A total of 2 of the 12 are in intensive care while the rest were discharged.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[During the West Nile virus transmission season (June to November), ECDC monitors the occurrence of West Nile fever cases in EU/EEA [European Economic Area] member states and neighbouring countries on a weekly basis in order to inform blood safety authorities of areas where there is ongoing virus transmission. During the 2017 transmission season, 288 human cases were reported in the EU and from neighbouring countries. No cases were reported from EEA countries. EU member states reported 127 equine cases.

"Between [Fri 6 and Thu 12 Jul 2018] (one week before the above report), 5 cases of human West Nile fever were reported in the EU. Greece reported one confirmed case in Thessaloniki and one probable case in Voiotia. Italy reported 3 confirmed cases, 2 in Modena and one in Rovigo. Serbia reported 9 confirmed human cases. All human cases were reported from regions that were also affected in previous transmission seasons.
[https://ecdc.europa.eu/sites/portal/files/documents/CDTR_14July2018.pdf].

The vector distribution maps are published regularly on the website to provide the ECDC stakeholders and the general public with the most up-to-date information on vector distribution, showing the distribution of the vector species at 'regional' administrative level .They can be accessed at https://ecdc.europa.eu/en/disease-vectors/surveillance-and-disease-data/tick-maps. - Mod.UBA

